    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Yordan Alvarez** (82.97) and **Junior Caminero** (71.00) represent the clear pillars of the Zurich Zebras lineup. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a highly favorable matchup against Gil (xERA 5.74), providing the highest raw ceiling of the day despite a minor park penalty. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** is primed for a productive outing in the two-hole against Woods Richardson, as he carries a strong SP skill advantage and a positive platoon edge that elevates his floor significantly. While we are prioritizing stolen bases, these two power threats provide the necessary stability to anchor a 5x5 lineup against mid-tier arms.\n\nNavigating the scarcity of speed requires careful deployment of players like **Victor Scott II** and **Caleb Durbin**. While **Victor Scott II** carries a lower score (53.24) due to a challenging SP skill rating (4.76 xERA) and an unfavorable batting position at #9, his elite sprint speed remains essential for our SB category targets. Conversely, **Caleb Durbin** benefits from a significant park factor boost, though he faces a tough assignment in Bradish (2.63 xERA). We remain wary of **Hyeseong Kim**, who sees his score dragged down to 46.77 by a direct platoon disadvantage against Imanaga; however, we are holding him in the lineup solely for the +5% wind-out projection, which slightly offsets his risk.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Carson Benge** (44.06). While his raw profile was competitive with the back-end of our starting outfield, his status remains \"Lineup Pending\" and the negative wind projections tipped the optimizer toward prioritizing the guaranteed playing time of **Luke Raley** (57.91). We are also monitoring **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (41.99), who was held out due to a severe platoon disadvantage against a left-handed starter, despite his potential to provide high-leverage speed on the basepaths. Finally, keep a close watch on **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber**; both are battling elite SP skill ratings from Sale (2.88 xERA), making their ability to produce today highly dependent on their respective lineup positioning to generate counting stats despite the pitcher dominance.",
